NLP: Transfer learning for non-IMDB movie review word embeddings

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE, cache = FALSE)

# Initialize package
library(keras)
library(tidyverse)
library(fs)
movie_dir <- here::here("docs", "data", "non-imdb-reviews")
training_files <- movie_dir %>%
  dir_ls() %>%
  map(dir_ls) %>%
  set_names(basename) %>%
  plyr::ldply(data_frame) %>%
  set_names(c("label", "path"))

training_files
count(training_files, label)
obs <- nrow(training_files)
labels <- vector(mode = "integer", length = obs)
texts <- vector(mode = "character", length = obs)

for (file in seq_len(obs)) {
  label <- training_files[[file, "label"]]
  path <- training_files[[file, "path"]]
  
  labels[file] <- ifelse(label == "neg", 0, 1)
  texts[file] <- readChar(path, nchars = file.size(path)) 
  
}
labels <- as.array(labels)
top_n_words <- 10000

tokenizer <- text_tokenizer(num_words = top_n_words) %>% 
  fit_text_tokenizer(texts)

Next, since each review is a different length, we need to limit ourselves to a certain number of words so that all our features (reviews) are the same length.

Note (?pad_sequences): * Any reviews that are shorter than this length will be padded. * Any reviews that are longer than this length will be truncated.

max_len <- 500
features <- pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen = max_len)
features[1,]
  [1]    1    8  770  141    9  657    3   21    1   84   14    6   25    2  295   46  948 1649  731   37   50    5  177    8   84   85  371
 [28]    6  682 6792    8    1  521    6  137 1132   11    1  440    9   71 3210  460   76  174  714    3   32   69 1487   19    1 7443  193
 [55]  194 1045 2853    9 3980 4204  504   28    2 2214    4 7099 1003  640 1211  302 1446 1315  314 1211  302    1 2518 1853  302    1 2518
 [82] 7100  749  302  341 4203  302  302 8855  302  302    1  485 1853  302 4341    4 3864 1022  302
paste(unlist(tokenizer$index_word)[features[1,]], collapse = " ")
set.seed(123)
index <- sample(1:nrow(features))

x_train <- features[index, ]
y_train <- labels[index]
model_basic <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(
    input_dim = top_n_words,  # number of words we are considering
    input_length = max_len,   # length that we have set each review to
    output_dim = 16            # length of our word embeddings
    ) %>%  
  layer_flatten() %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid") %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
)

history_basic <- model_basic %>% fit(
  x_train, y_train,
  epochs = 20,
  batch_size = 32,
  validation_split = 0.3,
  callbacks = list(
    callback_early_stopping(patience = 3, restore_best_weights = TRUE)
    )
)
model_lstm <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(
    input_dim = top_n_words,  # number of words we are considering
    input_length = max_len,   # length that we have set each review to
    output_dim = 16            # length of our word embeddings
    ) %>%  
  layer_lstm(units = 32) %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid") %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
)

history_lstm <- model_lstm %>% fit(
  x_train, y_train,
  epochs = 20,
  batch_size = 32,
  validation_split = 0.3,
  callbacks = list(
    callback_early_stopping(patience = 3, restore_best_weights = TRUE)
    )
)
